<dl id="n54146e"> <dt class="nbunit"><a name="n54" href="#n54146e">N54 (VI.B.45)</a>:  <a href="../../FF/fnbs/n54all.htm#n54146e"> 146(e)</a></dt> <dd> <blockquote> village stone <small>Green</small></blockquote> <dd class="well"> <ul class="list-inline" id="n54146e"> <li>FW unlocated</li> </ul> <blockquote class="sources">note 1: J. H. Hutton, Census of India, 1931, 1, pp. 408-409. &mdash; Chez les Bataks. le pangoeloebalang est une pierre &eacute;rig&eacute;e pr&egrave;s d&apos;un village. Souvent cette pierre est grossi&egrave;rement taill&eacute;e en forme de t&ecirc;te humaine&hellip; <mark>Ces pierre,, <font color="green">[sic]</font> de village</mark> se retrouvent chez beaucoup de populations de l&apos;archipel indon&eacute;sien. Leur destination est partout la m&ecirc;me: elles assurent le bien-&ecirc;tre. la prosp&eacute;rit&eacute;, la f&eacute;condit&eacute; et la sant&eacute; des villageois&raquo;. <br><font color="green">[J. H. Hutton, Census of India, 1931, 1, pp. 408-409. At the Bataks. the pangoeloebalang is a stone erected near a village. Often this stone is roughly cut in the shape of a head human &hellip; These village stones are found in many populations of the Indonesian archipelago. Their destination is the same everywhere: they ensure well-being. prosperity, fertility and the health of the villagers".]</font> <small> Lucian L&eacute;vy-Bruhl, <a name="LBEM" href="../../FF/fdra/fdex.htm#LBEM"><cite title="source">L'exp&eacute;rience mystique</cite></a> (1938) 209</small></blockquote> </dd></dl>
